    Metrics demo

    Demo of basic health metrics using RGB and HSV values.

    HSV preferred as more invariance to light levels.

def adjust_gamma(image, gamma=1.0):
    inv_gamma = 1.0 / gamma
    table = np.array([((i / 255.0) ** inv_gamma) * 255 for i in np.arange(0, 256)]).astype("uint8")
    return cv2.LUT(image, table)


healthy_sample_dark = adjust_gamma(image[400:440, 422:462], 0.7)
unhealthy_sample_dark = adjust_gamma(image[660:700, 428:468], 0.7)

mask = np.ones((40, 40)).astype(np.uint8)
mask = mask.astype(np.bool)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)
for ax, img, name in zip(
    axs.flatten(),
    [healthy_sample, unhealthy_sample, healthy_sample_dark, unhealthy_sample_dark],
    ["Healthy", "Unhealthy", "Healthy Dark", "Unhealthy Dark"],
):
    ax.set_title(name)
    ax.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB), interpolation="nearest")

    RGB approach

    def extract_rgb(image, mask):
    """flattens and masks pixels. Returns channel values."""
    assert image.shape[0] == mask.shape[0]
    assert image.shape[1] == mask.shape[1]
    flat_image = image.reshape(-1, 3)
    flat_mask = mask.reshape(-1)
    pixels = flat_image[flat_mask]
    # BGR
    b = pixels[:, 0]
    g = pixels[:, 1]
    r = pixels[:, 2]
    return r, g, b


def healthy_rgb(image, mask):
    """Return a boolean mask of healthy pixels."""
    r, g, b = extract_rgb(image, mask)
    healthy = np.logical_and(g > 50, g < 230)
    return healthy
    def extract_rgb(image, mask): """flattens and masks pixels.     Similar approach using HSV color space

    In[7]:
    Copied! 
    def calculate_hsv(image, mask):
    assert image.shape[0] == mask.shape[0]
    assert image.shape[1] == mask.shape[1]

    hsv_img = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)

    flat_image = hsv_img.reshape(-1, 3)

    flat_mask = mask.reshape(-1)

    pixels = flat_image[flat_mask]
    h = pixels[:, 0]

    s = pixels[:, 1]

    v = pixels[:, 2]

    return h, s, v
    def calculate_hsv(image, mask): assert image.shape[0] == mask.shape[0] assert image.shape[1] == mask.shape[1] hsv_img = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV) flat_image = hsv_img.reshape(-1, 3) flat_mask = mask.reshape(-1) pixels = flat_image[flat_mask] h = pixels[:, 0] s = pixels[:, 1] v = pixels[:, 2] return h, s, v
